gotiation strategies during the Korean armistice, and morale studies in the Vietnam era. Robin examines factors that shaped the scientists' thinking and explores their psycho-cultural and rational choice explanations for enemy behavior. He reveals how the academics' intolerance for complexity ultimately reduced the nation's adversaries to borderline psychotics, ignored revolutionary social shifts in post-World War II Asia, and promoted the notion of a maniacal threat facing the United States. Putting the issue of scientific validity aside, Robin presents the first extensive analysis of the intellectual underpinnings of Cold War behavioral sciences in a book that will be indispensable reading for anyone interested in the era and its legacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAftermath of World War II.  aAggression.  aAnti-Americanism.  aAnti-capitalism.  aAnti-communism.  aAnti-individualism.  aAnti-intellectualism.  aAntipathy.  aAphorism.  aArmistice.  aAuthoritarianism.  aBehavioralism.  aBehavioural sciences.  aBernard Brodie (military strategist).  aCarpet bombing.  aClash of Civilizations.  aCold War.  aCommunism.  aCommunist International.  aCommunist propaganda.  aConventional warfare.  aCounter-insurgency.  aCounter-revolutionary.  aCounter-terrorism.  aCreation myth.  aCriticism.  aCulture war.  aDecolonization.  aDefection.  aDemoralization (warfare).  aDeterrence theory.  aDisarmament.  aDisenchantment.  aDistrust.  aEspionage.  aExplanation.  aForeign policy.  aGlobal catastrophic risk.  aIdeology.  aIncest.  aIndoctrination.  aInsurgency.  aIsolationism.  aKorean War.  aKorean conflict.  aLoss of China.  aMilitarism.  aMilitarization.  aMind control.  aModerniza